Saturday, January 1, 1966

A bad start for herpetology in 1966, but not unexpected. Spent practically the entire day watching T.V.

First there was the Pasadena Rose Parade. Lucy Bell came over to watch it. The new rotating antenna worked fine. Then watched the Sugar Bowl at New Orleans. Missouri (20) vs Florida (18); then a part of the Cotton Bowl between Arkansas (7) and LSU (14), the latter winning.

Then the Rose Bowl which UCLA surprised everyone by winning over Michigan State that UCLA won 14 to 12. Then finally a short piece of the Orange Bowl ( Nebraska (28) vs Alabama (38) )

After supper I took in the Jackie Gleason, Lawrence Welk , and Hollywood Palace shows. They were good except the last which was spotty.

The Rose Bowl was almost too much for one in excitement, but by taking some pills I got by.

I was on Zoorama last night; a discussion of the rattle that had been taped early in the year.

Sunday, January 2, 1966

Watched the Packer-Cleveland game 11 to 2.

Did some work in the basement; made the special counts on the two LSUM intermedius intermedius.

Took down the Christmas lights and did some other miscellaneous work.

Monday, January 3, 1966

At the office this morning. A busy time. Much mail to read. Wrote a number of letters. Went to the bank and the library. Ordered several items from the National Medical Library.

Went to a lunch at the Zoo given for Dr. Herudon G. Dowling of the Bronx Zoo. Among others Schroeder, Shaw, Joe Copp, Etheridge and Hunsake were there. Got home at 2:30.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/15/2012 04:32 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Tuesday, January 4, 1966

At the office this morning.

Worked on carding; also briefly on Shaw's suggestion for Chapter 2.

Had banks balance my savings accounts. This took over an hour because so many people were doing the same thing.

At noon went to a luncheon at the Zoo where Howard Cheruoff told us about his Washington and travel experiences on U.S. Information service. Got home at 2:30.

The Millers came to call tonight.

Checked off Xmas cards on the receipt list.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/15/2012 04:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Wednesday, January 5, 1966

At the office this morning.

Carding, letter writing and other miscellaneous work.

Don Clark came in and we talked Natural History Museum business from 10 until 11:10.

Went to the bank and completed first-of-the-year financial transactions. Made a savings account deposit.

Spent the afternoon and evening figuring year-end accounts.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/15/2012 04:38 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Thursday, January 6, 1966

At the office this morning.

Conference with Sinnott on rate matters.

Completed one copy of Shaw suggestions on the Ms. Now the job is to make sure the duplicate copy of the MS has all the corrections and send one copy to the Press. This will be up to the end of Chapter 2.

Went over to the Library and cleaned up a few items. Worked on Reader's Guide to Periodical Literature.

In the afternoon, after 3, cleaned up various items.

Friday, January 7, 1966

At the office this morning.

Wrote several letters.

Bought the two copies of the Ms up to similarity so that both copies contain Shaw's and other recent changes. Got as far p 51 of Chapter 2 which was very good progress. Shouldn't be very long before one copy should be sent to U.C., that is to end of Chapter 2.

Meeting Planning Committee of S.D. Society of Nat History 4:30 to 5:45 P.M.

Saturday, January 8, 1966

This morning I continued comparing the two Ms copies of Chapter 2 and made good progress. Also did some work on Catalinensis and intermedius intermedius in the basement.

Went to a dinner party at Lenore Forward's tonight. A pleasant affair, but a foggy drive, both ways.

Sunday, January 9, 1966

Allan and Jean came in this morning. Talked over various business matters with Allen.

Went to Coronado at noon and had lunch with Col. Kelly and Christianne at the Coronado Hotel. Got home about 4.

Worked on Chapter 2 at 5 and from then on until 8:15. Got a lot done in sorting and arranging, getting nearer to the time when the Ms to the end of Chapter 2 can be sent to the Press.

Monday, January 10, 1966

At the office this morning.

Worked on Chapter 2 comparisons but didn't make good headway as I had failed to take down the right material and had to go home for it.

Meeting of the Publications Committee of the Natural History Museum 3:15 to 4:10; followed by a meeting of the Directors until after 5.

Page Edit History:

Tuesday, January 11, 1966

At the office this morning.

Finished the correction of both Ms copies of Chapter 2 to the end, especially the footnotes and their numbers. Next job will be to work on the figure numbers.

Went to the Library for an hour or more and cleared up a number of items. Changed the date of my snake talk to the children to April 1 so this will leave me free for going to the Los Angeles Museum Herp. meeting.

Went to a luncheon at the Zoo for 3 traveling members of the NSF. I didn't stay for a tour of some Zoo exhibits or a later meeting scheduled for the Natural History Society.

Went out to call on Jeffery and Chris this evening at their apartment on West California street. He is going into the service tomorrow and she is going back to work at Sea World.

Then to the SD Symphony Concert. First in concert arrangement of Wagner's Ring followed by Brahms Concert No. 2 played by Eugene Istomin. Both very good.

Wednesday, January 12, 1966

At the office this morning.

Worked on Chapter 2 Ms, inserting changed figure numbers for the identification series of plates; also the maps. A complicated set of changes.

Went to Jim Devel's funeral at 1:45; returned at 2:45. Met all his family.

Someone called me from Portland, Oregon and asked me to participate in a symposium on the desert. I failed to get the name, and , anyway declined. Said I was too old.

Thursday, January 13, 1966

At the office this morning after calling at the Bohemian Bakery for stuff to send the kids. Got some miscellaneous work done that took quite a bit of time. Then again tackled the figure-number changes in Chapter 2, an exceedingly time-consuming and complicated job. Made progress.

Continued making these changes this afternoon and evening. Made progress until I got tired out.

Friday, January 14, 1966

At the office for a short time. Wrote letters.

Meeting of the Library Commission 9:45 to 11:40.

Worked this afternoon changing figure numbers in the Ms of the Keys in Chapter 2. An exceedingly complicated job, with 3 separate series of numbers requiring changes.

Elwyn came to dinner tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 12:52 PM

Saturday, January 15, 1966

Today I continued work on Chapter 2, particularly changing figure numbers, and finished one copy of the Ms. Now I will have to make a second copy for safety; one to go to Berkeley; the other to be retained.

Fixed the pilot light in the basement--a touch job for me as it involved a lot of crawling. And I had to go back a second time because I dropped a pair of glasses.

Went to the Gentlemen of Distinction (of which I was one) at the International Room, El Cortez tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 12:57 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Sunday, January 16, 1966

Today I finished correcting the second copy of the Ms of Chapter 2. A detailed job that was hard on the eyes.

There are only one or two minor possible corrections left to pick up.

Watched a little pro football.

Millers came around this noon and repaired the fence east of our property.

Went to the Jack Benny - San Diego Symphony Concert tonight. It was quite amusing and we had a good time.

We then went to a post-concert reception at the Palm Room of the U S Grant. I got very tired and didn't enjoy it. We didn't get home until 12:30+. I shouldn't have gone, but I did get a chance to talk business with Walt Zitlau.

Page Edit History:

Monday, January 17, 1966

At the office today. Meeting of the Executive Committee until noon, followed by a meeting of the Board of Directors until 3.

Page Edit History:

Tuesday, January 18, 1966

At the office most of the morning. Spent most of the time arranging the parts of Chapter 2, so they would be ready to send to the Press. Made a good deal of progress.

Went to the library where they had several interlibrary loans ready for me, then went to the Savings Bank to meet Mrs. Heller, but she had forgotten the safety deposit box key, so we couldn't do the work we intended.

In the afternoon worked on the kitchen faucet. I think I have it fixed for awhile I hope.

Got back Phylogeny and Zoogeography from Miss Molloy; she had mislaid the manuscript.

Page Edit History:

Wednesday, January 19, 1966

This was a day of smog meetings. First to the office for a short time; then to a meeting 10 to 12:15 of the State Motor Vehicle Pollution Control Board at the State Building; then in the afternoon 3 to 5:15 a meting of the Southern California Air Pollution Coordinating Council. I didn't participate in either meeting. Although I was introduced at the first.

Had my chev's brakes repaired at a nearby repair shop during the morning meeting. Askew took me home for lunch and I called for the car after lunch. The brakes were found in bad shape.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 01:15 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Thursday, January 20, 1966

At the office this morning.

Went to the bank twice.

Worked on a letter to the Press about the manuscript I was sending (the end of Chapter 2).

This afternoon worked on a talk on Snakes of San Diego County to be given at Francis Parker School tomorrow afternoon.

Worked late this evening straightening out the identification series of photos and their legends. Only partly successful.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 01:18 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Friday, January 21, 1966

Got up early this morning and worked on the snake talk for Francis Parker.

Also looked for the missing Jennings' letter about photos.

At the office part of the morning. Then went to the Library. Made progress with Biological Abstracts, clearing up all but the latest number, not yet available.

Went over to the Engineering Bldg and saw Kobler. Decided not to undertake any further work on the intermedius intermedius picture, but to use as is.

Made a talk on snakes of San Diego County before an assembly of three classes (grades 7 to 9) at Francis Parker School. I think it went OK. There were plenty of questions. This lasted from 2:30 to 3:15.

Joe Copp came in this afternoon and got his two Sonora rattlers -- atrox and tigris.

Saturday, January 22, 1966

Spent all morning preparing a chronology of the second edition of Rattlesnakes. Went over the correspondence and found that becoming more familiar with it made correspondence with Walters, the editor, considerably easier.

Spent the afternoon on a long letter to Walters discussing the Ms up to the end of Chapter 2 that I shall send him early next week.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, January 23, 1966

Worked all day on the Ms up to the end of Chapter 2 and one set is now practically ready to send to Berkeley.

Also finished the letter to Walters at Berkeley.

Tried to fix the kitchen-sink faucets this evening and wrecked the outfit.

Page Edit History:

Monday, January 24, 1966

Got up at 3 and cleared up a lot of miscellaneous filing and other work I was too tired to tackle last night. Worked until about 5.

At the office this morning.

Wrote letters. Went shopping for a Kitchen faucet. Checked Sloan's scale counts against the tables, looking for new maxima and minima.

Packing packages this afternoon.

A big hen party at home tonight. I was too tired to get much done.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 01:39 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Tuesday, January 25, 1966

Got up at 4:15 and cleared up my desk of various unfinished items, especially photos.

Worked until 6.

At the office this morning. Worked on photographs and other material.

In the afternoon tried to install the new faucet in the kitchen sink. Worked hard and wore myself out but had no luck as the old piping to which it had to be attached was badly corroded so that there was a leak.

Went to San Diego Symphony concert tonight. Carlos Chavez was the guest conductor. It was an interesting and enjoyable concert.

Page Edit History:

Wednesday, January 26, 1966

At the office most of the morning. Did some shopping. Not a very productive day. Conference with Phil about the Symphony Orchestra.

The plumber came to day and installed the kitchen sink faucet. The old piping was so badly corroded I never could have made the installation.

Called for Laurie at the Grant School at 2:30.

Mailed the Ms, up to and including Chapter 2, to the U. C. Press today with a long letter of transmittal.

Meeting of the Zoo Trustees tonight. I got beat on asking for alternative designs for the Education Bldg looking to a square or rectangular building instead of the round building no contemplated.

Thursday, January 27, 1966

At the office this morning.

Wrote letters.

Worked on taking off data from my cash book for annual inventory and for income tax. Made pretty fair progress.

Went to a meeting (lunch) at the 24th floor of the First National Bank Building of the Library Committee on special gifts and the Library Commission.

Bert Lynch called from Chicago re health insurance and the change in our status.

Called Fred Kunzel tonight and discussed the Education Building further asking him to vote against extras.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/28/2014 11:08 AM

Friday, January 28, 1966

At the office this morning.

Made some progress with the annual inventory and data fom income tax.

Went to Ruth Budrow's funeral at 11:30 and then up to the Budrow home with all the friends and relatives for lunch.

Repaired the lamp at my bed this afternoon. Also checked my checking account.
____________________________________________________________
(Saturday, Mar 5, continued)

The first order of business at the meeting was for each educator to outline the research work being carried on at his institution.

Al Leviton and Steve Anderson pf CAS are working on the reptiles of southeast Asia; also on the electrophoresis of venoms and blood, which they thought had much promise in showing relationships.

(From here I have most of the names wrong.)

Jameson spoke for San Diego State. Frank Audrey is working on frog calls with a new apparatus, and Hunsaker on behavior. Etheridge is working on the difference between agamids and iguanids. He is finding much that is new and important in scale organs including hair-like features. Bill Presch is studying the oseology of Phrynosoma.

Farrington of U.C. Riverside and ---- from Colombia are working on the water absorption of toads. Dennis Clauson is working on water losses in lizards.

(Continued on Jan 29)

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 02:04 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Saturday, January 29, 1966

Worked all day on annual inventory and data for income tax and made considerable progress.
______________________________________________________________________________________________________________
(March 5 continued from Jan 28)

Herb Brown is working on Scaphiopus and Joe Weintraub on S. orcutti. Bill Mayhem is in Egypt. Paul Madison of England & Australia is working on snake and lizard skins - the shedding of the old skin and the formation of the new layers. He described the sequence. He said he had found Rattlenakes very useful.

Loomis of Long Beach is busy with extoparasite. He is willing to identify any mites submitted. He mentioned several people who are working on Uta stanburiana.

Brattstrom reported several people working on the effects of temperature on rattlesnake behavior. He leaves shortly for a year in Australia.

Red Turner of UCLA is busy at the Nevada Test Site. Ken Norris came in late and described other work at UCLA.

Jay Savage reported on many projects at USC.

Roze discussed the herpetologists of South America and their activities.

For lunch we walked over to a USC beer joint on Figueroa St. It was dark, poor food, and a long walk for me. Fortunately I got a ride back.

After lunch there were more outlines of projects.

(Continued on Jan. 30)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/28/2014 11:10 AM
  • pamg 12/16/2012 02:16 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Sunday, January 30, 1966

At 12 KV line diagonally across the street fell in a windstorm about 5:30 this morning. They tried the circuit 3 or 4 times which caused a big flash each time and there was plenty of excitement. I called the trouble dept and they had men up promptly. Some one else turned in a fire alarm so we had a truck and police. There seemed to be no particular damage. A line truck came up and repaired the lines early this morning.

Worked all day on the annual inventory and income tax. The former is finished except for some figures I must get down town. The income tax figures have been taken off the books. Next I must make up the supplemental sheets to accompany the report, and then prepare the return.
________________________________________________________________
(March 5 continued from Jan 29)

I gave a brief talk on C. scutalatus to prove the taxonomy can have some particular value.

We then saw the collection and the progress they are making in accessioning. I went over the rattler cards, but saw nothing of particular interest. Took a taxi back to the hotel. Had a long wait for it. Had another long walk for a fruit stand and finally located one near 7th and Flower. Was quite worn out.

(Continued on Jan 31)

Monday, January 31, 1966

At the office this morning.

Went to the bank to get some necessary papers out of my safe-deposit box.

Dictated letters.

Worked a little on annual inventory.

In the afternoon, finished the annual inventory and got back on income tax, particularly the justification sheets.
_______________________________________________________________
(March 5 continued from Jan. 30)

Had supper at the Beltmore Coffee shop, and then watched TV.

Went to the Millers for dinner tonight. Very good. Gracie was home.

Saturday, February 5, 1966

Worked all day on income tax calculations and finished the first draft which will now require rechecking. What I owe is much larger than last year because the credit for contributions is made smaller. Last year the herp collection greatly reduced taxes. This year there is only a small carry forward.

Went to the Charity Ball at Coronado tonight. Dinner with Hellers, Violet, Oscar, Benny, Fanny Sherman. Also the Wohlford cocktail party. Home at midnight.

Sunday, February 6, 1966

Up late this morning because of late hours last night.

Spent the day on income tax. The 1965 return is now ready to be copied. I back checked all the figures, and hope they are right, including the supporting data sheets.

Had a short conference with Joe Sinnott.

Pach came in and we discussed auto insurance and other matters.

Went to San Diego Symphony concert tonight. Very good. Enjoyed Patricia Michaelian, pianist, age 15 in a Mozart concerts.

Called for bakery goods at the Bohemian Bakery for Gracie and Larry before going to the office.

Expected to finish Federal Income Tax return this morning, but found an error in what I had previously prepared and didn't have the necessary data a the office to correct it. So I worked on carding pamphlets of which there was quite an accumulation. Got a considerable amount of this done.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/28/2014 11:52 AM

Thursday, February 10, 1966

Got up this morning before 5 and straightened out an income tax problem. I had not taken credit for the effect of an overpayment the previous year. This leads to a complication that I had not recognized. It somewhat reduces my taxes. I don't have to make a payment until April 15 by which time I shall have accumulated some additional funds which will reduce the necessary withdrawal from savings.

At the office this morning. Made some changes in the income tax return. Now all I need will be some additional copies and then I shall file all the papers until about April 1.

Went to the post office, library, and zoo. Took the last-years Xmas cards to the Zoo.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/16/2012 08:19 PM

Friday, February 11, 1966

Got up at 3:30 and reread Slvan's Baja California Island paper.

St the office this morning and had a busy day cleaning up many odds and ends.

Conferences with Stanley Jewell on some early Escondido PVC cases. Also with Joe Sinnott on use of city streets.

Have 1965 Federal Income Tax return ready to submit any time.

Page Edit History:

Saturday, February 12, 1966

Spent a lot of time today rearranging my desk file of papers and records and completed what I think is a good job. Will save time in the future.

Then worked on the carding the separates that have recently accumulated. Made a good dent but didn't finish catching up.

Watched Zoorama this evening. I was on in the discussion of the nomenclature of reptiles, including Lichanura roseofusca gracia.

Sunday, February 13, 1966

This morning finished the carding.

At noon went to lunch with the Col. William Kellys at Coronado Hotel. Went with the Dallas Clarks and Frank Wakefield. Got home at 4:30.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 12/23/2012 09:12 PM

Monday, February 14, 1966

At the office this morning.

Saturday, February 19, 1966

Was once more impressed by the difference of willardi from other rattlers, in their head scales and patterns.

Went to Scholia tonight; Rabbi Cohn talked on the population explosion, a subject on which I was able to add a comment or two.

Tuesday, February 22, 1966

This morning I rearranged the data on MVZ specimens and Sloan's scale counts so that specimens could be packed and returned to their owners.

Took GG's car down to Taylor's agency to be services. Called for it in the later afternoon.

Went over to the Natural History Museum and presided at a session of the American Assn. of Zoological Parks and Aquariums. Carl Kauffeld of the Staten Island Zoo talked on Rattlesnakes in Captivity and showed some fine color slides. There were no questions.

Then Findlay E. Russell talked on Snake Venom Poisoning, also with colored slides of injuries. His talk was most interesting and elicited many questions, so that Clyde Hill's talk on Madagascar had to be postponed.

Went over to Bali Hai on Shelter Island. Stood around a long time waiting for service until I was thoroughly worn out. Got home about 4.

As usual the most profitable part of the session was meeting the various visiting herpetologists of who there were many - too many to recall. Had lunch with Shaw, Fin Russsell, Ray Folsom and several others.

Went to San Diego Symphony Concert tonight. An enjoyable affair. Phillip and Detty June picked us up.

Barry Simmons came in at 2:30 to make a 15 min tape to be used by U.S. Information Service. We worked on it until 4. His method was to ask questions about rattlers to which I replied. We first went over their data so he got familiar with some of the facts of rattler habits and activities. Of course we missed a lot of points in the final tape, but on the whole I think it went OK. He didn't select quite the items I would have preferred to use.

Friday, March 4, 1966

At the office this morning. Wrote letters. Getting ready for the trip to LA. Went home to check the mail.

Caught the 1 PM train for Los Angeles. Left the Chev. at the Santa Fe Station in SD. Had an uneventful trip except that we had to carry our baggage into the station, because the little carts were all in use. Got a little reading done on the train but not much.

The Biltmore room was OK.

Went out shopping at about 4. Bought a dozen pairs of socks at the Army-Navy store where I have got them before. Walked around looking for a fruit stand to buy some oranges for breakfast and got pretty tired doing so. No luck. All the little shops have been frozen out by high-rise buildings.

Had dinner at the Biltmore Coffee Shop. It wasn't much good. Walked around again looking for fruit stands I used to know. No soap. Got tired out.

Page Edit History:
  • Will 03/28/2014 02:22 PM
  • pamg 12/23/2012 10:34 PM

Saturday, March 5, 1966

Took a taxi out to the LA County Museum at Exposition Park where the herp. get-together was to be held. Was set down at the wrong place, so I had a long tiring walk to the right building. But I finally found it and was in plenty of time for the meeting. James K Dixon, formerly of Texas A and M is the new curator of herpetology and they have elaborate plans for the expansion of the department, as I found out later. They are going to combine all the herp. collections in the vicinity of LA (have done much of it already) into a single collection which will be highly desirable from the standpoint of users and borrowers. This will include UCLA, USC, and the state colleges, such as LA, Fullerton, San Fernando, Long Beach, etc. It will comprise a large collection. They have plenty of room and some of the cataloging is already complete.

There were about 40 or 50 herps present at the meeting. Those I knew best were Levinton of CHS, Savage of USC, Brattstrom of Fullerton, Loomis of Long Beach, Roza of Venezuela and AMNH etc.

Janis Roze's paper on the Orinoco River Turtle given last night was warmly praised. They said the movies were fantastic.

Etheridge and Jameson from SD State were there. Sloan from SD for Nat. History came late.

(Continued on Friday, Jan 28)

Sunday, March 6, 1966

This morning I went out and bought a Sunday Union so we had plenty to do.

Had breakfast at the Coffee Shop.

In the early afternoon we went to one of the cafes in the Music Center where we had a reservation.

Then we went to a choral concert conducted by Robert Shaw. It was very good although there was some modern stuff I didn't take to.

After the concert we went up to the Founder's Lounge where about 200 people were milling around yaking and drinking. We waited for Shaw thinking that when he came in this mob would gather round him and make it impossible for us to get within speaking range. We got in by using Mrs Price's name (Shaw's sister). But it didn't work this way. When he finally showed up no one paid any attention to him - they were only interested in drinks. So we had a pleasant chat and then returned to the Biltmore which we reached about 10:30. We had a tough time getting a taxi.

Thursday, March 24, 1966

Worked on state income tax, particularly the retirement income credit. Finished this and tried to make Thermofax copies, but they turned out badly, even when using special Thermofax ink.

Went up to the bank and transferred enough from my savings account to the checking a/c to permit paying both federal and state taxes with a remainder of working cash to spare.

Called up Dr. Fishburn and got a brief verbal report on my recent examination. The blood sugar came out OK but the urine showed bacteria. Will take the red pills previously prescribed by Dr. Howe for 3 or 4 days; then leave a sample at Fishburn's office 2 days after quitting pills. Cancelled barium X-ray tests scheduled for next Sunday-Tuesday as hip is improved.

Worked on Duellman's paper (Cont. on Mar 23)

Anyway things are in a lot better order.

Went to a dinner tonight given at Kona Kai by Sheldon Campbell and the Zoo - 50 year committee. Purpose was to meet Baroness Jane van Lawick-Goodall (the chimp girl ) and the Baron. Had a good dinner and a good time. Small tables. Sat with the Shaws and Jane. It was noisy so I didn't hear too much. Gray and Sullivan were the only other Zoo trustees present. Got home at 1:00.

Sunday, April 3, 1966

Got up early and went over Chapter 3 and destroyed all superseded copies of preliminary drafts. What is left is now greatly reduced and simplified.

This morning I overhauled Paleontology and it is now finished including spaces for the insert. The Thermofax ms is OK as to content but not very good to submit to the Press. Will have to see what is available as a spare and also consider the preparation of a better xerox to become the basic ms. The inserts are OK and there are two up to date spares.

Worked on the second part of Chapter 3 Phylogeny and Zoogeography and see that I am going to have a tough time interdigitating the old part, phylogeny as published in Ed 1 with the new, only partly written part stressing Zoogeography with its many new references.

Spent considerable time this afternoon making up a second ms. copy of paleontology. Want to have an office copy to play safe. For the present I can consider paleontology behind me.

Tuesday, April 26, 1966

A hard day today, and just about exhausted tonight.

At the office. Bert Lynch came in about 9:25 and we chatted until 10; all about Chicago, Byllesky and old times. Then went to Annual meeting of stockholders that lasted until 11. Was uneventful.

Then I started out to Santee to look for Prospect Ave school where I am to give a talk on Thursday. Got completely off the track several times but finally located it. Good thing I did as I never would have got there on time the first try. Fanita Ave was confused with Anita and Bonita. Got home about 4:30.

Unpacked specimens of intermedius gloydi from Hobart Smith: sorry they aren't intermedius intermedius that I need much worse.

Got Sloan's island paper; must make copies of some parts.

Wednesday, April 27, 1966

At the office this morning. Cleared up a lot of biliographic work, carding, pink sheets, etc. Got a copy of Sloan's Island paper and reread it.

Hanson came out and looked over the house for repairs that should be made. He didn't think any mason work bad enough to require repair. But some of the leaky plumbing should be done, especially corroded fittings.

Zoo meeting of trustees tonight. Got badly beaten on advocacy of a bridge to the deer mesa ahead of a speed ramp.

Had a call tonight (about 11) from a Dr. Creutz (?) at Port Hueneme Ventura Co. Had a child bitten by a rattler. They were not sure of the snake and had no antivenine. I suggested he call the Ventura County Hospital. Told him there would be full instructions with the antivenene for testing for horse serum allergy. Called him back at 11:45; found it was a rattler. Gave him a few other ideas and asked him to let me know how the case came out.

Thursday, April 28, 1966

Went out to Santee via Mission Gorge this morning and talked to the children of the Prospect Avenue Grammar School about the snakes of San Diego County. I was well treated and all arrangements were quite satisfactory. I think there were about 500 kids in the auditorium. I left plenty of time for questions and there were plenty. All this took from 10 to 10:50.

Then I met with another, smaller class at 11:30 and answered questions until 12:00. The teacher was very helpful.

Heard from Shaw this afternoon. Ruthling's triseriatus has arrived.

The City Council met to discuss La Jolla. I didn't attend. Those who did say the situation is more confused than ever.

Tired tonight but otherwise OK. With these children's audiences my trouble is that I can't hear the questions.

Saturday, May 28, 1966

This morning I made some real progress with Zoogeography; maybe now I shall be able to squirm out of this road block which has been so disastrous for the past year. At best it will be a lousy job as might be expected of one who has completely lost his memory. This hasn't been because I have not undertaken the required research; I have almost done too much. But I can't whip it into good shape without making it too long; besides which I no longer have the required organizing ability. If I ever crawl out of this impasse, I shall try to avoid getting into a similar one in the subsequent chapters.

In the afternoon I made some more progress, rearranging the accumulated notes so as to utilize the necessary ones.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 01/15/2013 05:34 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Sunday, May 29, 1966

Got up at 4:30 and made some further progress with species peculiarities.

Made good progress with Zoogeography today and fitted the finished sections together. They coordinate fairly well and I now have a preliminary write up that needs only some limited additions (and a few eliminations) to complete it. Limited additions will be no means exhaust my knowledge of the subject, which will be a rather sketchy exposition in any case, but it will be plenty long enough and should not be elaborated. What is needed more than anything else is an outline of how and when the U.S. species developed. Also Baja Calif islands.

At any rate I am now beginning to see daylight on Chapter 3.

Tonight worked on the noisy faucet in the laundry. Repacked it, but it still leaks. Must do it again.

Monday, May 30, 1966

Got up at 4 and went back to work on zoogeography. Still organizing the unfinished parts. Still not complete by a long way but the route to completion is moderately clear. At least it is closer than it was before and the end is in sight.

Another lousy day due to bad programing. Hoped to finish Chapter 3 but hardly made a start. Repaired the noisy faucet in the basement; then ditto with the east fence in the garden and the hot house arbor. These two jobs so tired me that I couldn't and didn't get back efficiently on the zoogeographic problems. Tried to but was too tired and sleepy. I should have finished the job today; instead I am as far away as I was yesterday. This ought to be a lesson for an old guy who tires with the lease physical work, but it probably won't be.

Dave called and asked me to write Larry about using his space time this week to get studying accomplished.

Friday, June 10, 1966

At the office this morning.

Finished the write-up on Baja California and the Islands. Will probably need some touching up, but in the main it's satisfactory. As this is a major item in the troublesome section on zoogeography I have really made a dent in the latter, at last and can begin to see daylight.

For safety I made a Thermofax copy of the above and will now turn it over to Miss Molly for copying on the typewriter.

Was too tired this morning to work after 11 but did go over to the library.

Continued work on zoogeography this afternoon and got in some good licks. Can begin to see daylight at last. There are a few short sections to write such as molossus - horridus and atrox - adamanteus, plus quite a bit of rearranging and organizing, but the end is in sight.

Dr. L. S. Conti, 12 Forest View Drive, Nevada City, Calif, called tonight. Wants me to write him doing what I can to kill the rattleless rattlesnake myth that is resulting in the destruction of harmless snakes in Nevada County, mostly gopher snakes.

Saturday, June 11, 1966

Got up at 3 this morning and started reorganizing the manuscript of Chapter 3. Particularly segregated Part 1, Paleontology from the succeeding parts Phylogeny and Zoogeography. Worked until 5.

This morning I worked indexing the parts of Zoogeography so far completed paragraph by paragraph. This is to improve the continuity of the development and to avoid duplications and conflicts. The basic writing is virtually complete but the several parts in which it was written badly need coordinating. Also I listed the unfinished items; there are not many.

This morning I received the 3 San Lorenzo Island rubers from the Calif Academy.

Feeling poorly today with a sharp stomach pain; nevertheless worked on some of the unfinished Chapter 3 items in the afternoon, especially the atrox - adamanteus relationship.

Although I felt pretty lousy, I continued to work on Zoogeography this afternoon and evening, and finished all but one of the remaining parts.
Of course the big job of correlation and continuity without duplication still remains. But daylight is in sight at last.

Saturday, June 18, 1966

This morning I had every intention of working on the San Lorenzo Island ruber and the gloydi borrowed from H M Smith so I could send them back to their owners, but I felt so lousy and got so exhausted that I had to quit.

I did a fairly good job in the ruber but that's as far as I got. There were 6 preserved (3 from CAS: 3 from S D Soc. Nat Hist ) and Shaws 4 live ones. I wouldn't do anything with the latter. With the former I found only one consistent character: a white vertical streak on the proximal lobe of the rattle matrix. The other characters for which I had some hopes were not consistent: they were all rattles missing but one; supraocular sutures; extra (3 small) internasals; missing durdid first infralabials. None of these held up except the first and this seems very unimportant.

Went down to the airport and picked up Gracie at 1:30

At the office this morning.

Saturday, July 16, 1966

Cleaned up a lot of odds and ends and files this morning. Rearranged Medicare and Health files.

Otherwise a very unproductive and disappointing day. Despite the virtual completion of Chapter 3 (at last) I simply couldn't get my teeth into it to wind it up.

In the evening I went out to El Cajon and talked on the snakes of San Diego County to the El Cajon Valley Gem and Mineral Society at Wells Park. I was asked to appear at 7:30 and got there at 7:15. They first had a business meeting including making arrangements for an entertaniment where with to raise funds. This lasted from 7:45 to 9:15, and was exceedingly dull for me. I talked from 9:20 to 9:45 and then there were questions which lasted until 10:05. I won the door prize, a piece of dolomite, because the number had been torn off my ticket. I got home at 11:00; came in on 94 and the traffic was something. I was quite worn out.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 01/19/2013 12:20 PM

Sunday, July 17, 1966

This morning I picked up Phylogeny and Zoogeography and finished it as far as I can until the material Miss Molloy is copying becomes available. I can then be quickly arranged and completed, duplicate stuff discarded, and the rest given Miss Molloy for copying.

So as Chapter 3 is practically finished as far as I can go until Miss Molloy produces some copying of manuscripts, it may be noted that I began my revision of this chapter on June 16, 1965. So it took a little over a year to revise it. Never again; I have learned my lesson; no other chapter will receive so extensive a revision. If it did of course I would never finish.

This afternoon I began on a small scale with the revision of Chapter 4; at least to the extent of pulling the pink sheets.

I found that I had already done (a year ago) considerable work on Chapter 4; but this was in the form suitable for a supplement (as then contemplated) and not for a second edition. So now this must be done over, but at least the data and statistics are already at hand.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 01/19/2013 12:26 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Monday, July 18, 1966

Was called last night by a Dr. Charles Hendrickson of Newport Beach. They had caught a snake (the police had it alive) that they thought was a coral snake. They were afraid it might have bitten some one but there was no such report. They were afraid there might be siblings about. The description didn't sound like a coral. Maybe Lampropeltis, Rhinocheilus, even Chionactis. I told him there was nothing to worry about. The snout was not black; to get an identification from Dr. James Dixon at LA County Museum in the morning. This was at 10:45 P.M. First time I ever heard of so much fuss about a snake that hadn't bitten anyone; that probably was not exotic anyway; and if not exotic, then harmless.

At the office this morning.

Meeting of Executive Committee, 10 to 12; directors 1 to 2.

Monday, September 5, 1966

Got started once more on Chapter 4. Did a lot of checking to pick up the program again. A fine example of how, if there is an interruption to the work, it takes a lot of time to get oriented again, and a lot of time is completely lost. My memory is such that I can never recall just what I was doing or where to insert new material. Steady application is the answer; without this I shall never make the grade.

Worked on Chapter 4 off and on most of the day and made some progress.

Friday, November 4, 1966

At the office this morning.

Dictated a couple of letters.

Spent the rest of the morning working on the Darwin speech, cutting out still more.

At noon gave the Darwin speech to the University Club. I think it went OK. I ate little lunch and sat down for the talk. The conditions were ideal; good lighting, etc; but still I stumbled a good deal where the writing on the slips was small and not too legible. I am certainly no longer good at reading unless the writing is large and clear. My voice seemed to carry OK. The talk lasted about 28 minutes which was OK.

Went to call on Chuck Leigh this afternoon. He had an operation recently.

Spent the evening cleaning up my desk, already with a new accumulation of chores. Got it into fair shape.

Saturday, November 19, 1966

This morning I got started on the oaxacus - nigrescens problem and made some progress.

Also gathered vegrandis data. After seeing the first live specimen I am convinced it is a full species and not a subspecies of durissus.

Received today from U.C. Press the first proofs of the material I sent in up to the conclusion of Chapter 2. This will take a lot of correcting work, complicated by Hoge's stuff, vegrandis as a species and macroscutus.

Watched the Michigan State-Notre Dame game (a tie 10-10) and the end of the UCLA-So. Cal game (14-7).

Tonight went to a dinner dance at the Art Gallery. A large and ornate affair. We sat with Lenore, Oscar, and Whitney's. A pretty good dinner but too much standing up. Got home at 10:45.

Tuesday, November 29, 1966

This is our 55th Wedding anniversary.

At the office this morning.

Had a long talk with Joe Sinnott; first about franchise payments, then about my continued working for the Company. I suggested that I resign effective Dec. 31 next as I was deteriorating rapidly and was of small use to the Company as a consultant. Joe promised to think it over; said he hasn't considered the matter recently and that's where it was left. I said I didn't want to embarrass him or the company with other employes. That's where the mater was left.

Today worked on the proofs of Chapter 1 and 2, making 2 copies of corrections. Also I still have to compare wit the ms. as sent to the press. It's a long-winded slow job.

Took the Whitmey's, Starkey's and Lenore and Oscar to the presymphony dinner at the Palm Room of the Grant. Then to the Concert of the San Diego Symphony, Chavez, guest conductor. Didn't care very much for the program.

Friday, December 2, 1966

At the office this morning.

Brief conference with Joe Sinnott.

Spent the morning checking the U.C. Press proofs against the original manuscripts of Chapters 1 and 2. Found a number of errors not disclosed by reading the proofs, as had already been done. This checking against the manuscript is very slow as the manuscript and proofs are very much chopped up, but it has been found absolutely essential. This entire morning only covered about 1/3 of the total, so much remains to be done. It's slow and hard on the eyes of an ancient dodo like me.

Even the white lines in the road were almost invisible. It was very ticklish work, and the traffic was heavy.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:13 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Monday, December 19, 1966

At the office this morning.

Meeting of the Executive Committee from 9:30 until noon; then meeting of the Board of Directors until 1:40.

A girl called up from San Bernardino this AM; wanted to know something about care of tegus. Referred her to Shaw at the Zoo, she said "What Zoo?"

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:18 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Tuesday, December 20, 1966

A busy day today.

First went to Natural History Museum; left candy for Sloan; also a letter to answer.

Then to the offic; dictated a letter to Chernoff and enclosed yesterday's Union Editorial warning Zoo to go slow on San Pasqual and watch economic effects.

Then to Library where I left many periodicals; also had a talk with Miss Breed about how to advance a new site at La Jolla.

To post office and made a final mailing of X mas cards; also bought stamps.

Then to bank where I transferred funds from savings to commercial account so I could fix up the PMF and Miller's Xmas gifts.

Met Kobler on street, he has received note on the most recent change in Lannomi.

In the afternoon J. H. Tashjian of Oakland called and showed me his ms. of the planned popular book on rattlers. Also his most recent pictures. He has left ms with Shaw to read. Will then transfer it to me.

Went to Wright-Phillips party at College Hts Chuck Wagon. Oscar Cotton drove us out. 17 present. Private bus.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 05/12/2014 03:56 PM
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:36 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Wednesday, December 21, 1966

At the office this morning.

Worked on comparing the Chapter 2 proofs with my original manuscript and finished it, pp 29-34, Slow and hard on the eyes as usual. This doesn't mean the job is finished there are many loose ends still to pick up. But at least the major objective is attained.

This evening went to a birthday party given for the family by Lect at the Top of the Cove at La Jolla. A good party. Every one but Allan present; he was sick.

Got home at 10; fortunately no fog.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:40 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Thursday, December 22, 1966

At the office this morning.

Caught up on reading.

Also did a lot of shopping. Nothing worth while accomplished.

Larry and Gracie came to supper tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:41 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Friday, December 23, 1966

At the office this morning.

Finished correcting the duplicate proofs.

Rechecked differences between C. b. basiliscus and C. b. oaxacus.

Worked on the table to incorporate as a footnote to include Hoge's new terrificus subspecies. Made progress but it's tough and unsatisfactory.

Mary Jane and Gary's wife with their young infants were waiting around at noon.

Jane and Timmie came to dinner tonight; then we went to a benefit movie at the New Valley Circle Theater for the Cart Association. Peter Sellers and Victor Mature in "After the Fox" a wild spoof of an Italian movie. Had a good time.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 05/12/2014 03:57 PM
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:46 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Saturday, December 24, 1966

Spent the morning checking the yellow manuscript sheets against the proofs of Chapter 1 and 2. A tough slow job because everything is so chopped up. Some new parts were certainly missing. Got about half through.

In the early afternoon went down town to get a Smothers Bros record for Janet. This took a lot of time but I made the grade.

Went to a family dinner at the Allan Klauber's tonight, all there including the Bosworths, their two little girls and his parents. A fine dinner, Got home at 11.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:49 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Sunday, December 25, 1966

Read the paper and got up late.

Went to Philip's about 10:30 and sat around, seeing what the kids had got for Christmas.

At one P.M. went to the Miller's for Christmas dinner. Sat around for awhile. Back to Heynemans for a package we had wrongly delivered.

Home at 4:30 and got a little rest.

Ruth Herickendorf and Randy Carter called at 5:00.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:51 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Monday, December 26, 1966

This was a holiday at home.

The first thing I did was to complete the checking of the yellow ms pages of Chapters 1 and 2 (including the footnotes) against the proofs. Finished this at about 10 AM.

Worked some on the identification series of cuts this afternoon but didn't make much progress.

Jay called for a visit this afternoon.

Spent the evening on my presentation of Hoge and made progress until I was tired out.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:54 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Tuesday, December 27, 1966

At the office this morning.

Had a conference with Walter Zitlau concerning employing Stanford Research to devise and infra-red detector that would disclose electric line connectors that were loose and heating, with the idea of avoiding failures and outages.

Worked on Hoge's South American Rattlers and prepared a footnote for Chapter 2 that would cover them, at least briefly.

16 people in to dinner tonight; everything went OK.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 11:57 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Wednesday, December 28, 1966

Went to the office this morning.

Went to the bank to straighten out check matters.

Did quite a bit of carding.

Worked on Hoge for a while but didn't make much progress.

Caught up on a pile of company reading.

Meeting of the Zoo Trustees tonight from 5:30 to 8:30. A fairly peaceful meeting. Will go ahead with the Standford Research Institute up dating of the San Pasqual report. Also Judge Kunzel and Andy Borthwick will conclude a deal with Peat Marwick & Mitchell for their report on Zoo operations and methods.

Listened to ABC summary of last years world events at Howard K Smith's Washington home. A good program.

Wrote a letter to Howard Chernoff until midnight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/20/2013 12:01 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Thursday, December 29, 1966

A bad day today. Took books to the Public Library on the way down; then to the P. O. to mail a package.

Didn't get to my office until 10 AM. Finished letter to Chernoff. Other miscellaneous catching up. Nothing done on the book.

Ted Myers came in for a visit at about 11:15 and stayed for a half hour or more.

Went to a performance of the Mikado by the D'Oyly Carte Opera Co tonight. Very melodious and enjoyable.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 05/12/2014 03:59 PM
  • pamg 02/20/2013 12:04 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:16 PM

Friday, December 30, 1966

At the office this moring. A cold wet day. Did a little carding; also worked some on Hoge, but didn't accomplish very much. Tired out very soon.

Tonight the Miller's took us to the Chuck Wagon for dinner, after which we went to D'Oyly Carte performance of The Pirates of Penzance, a very enjoyable performance.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 05/12/2014 03:59 PM

Saturday, December 31, 1966

This morning worked on my electric heater.

Finished carding the last Copeia.

Picked up some other odds and ends, but not much. A little football. Another wasted day.

Played some Gilbert and Sullivan.

Chuck Wagon

Midway Chuck Wagon
Midway Drive at Rosecrans
San Diego 6, Calif.

Delicious choice of prime ribs -- all you can eat for $2.29 is the slogan of the Midway Chuck Wagon. Customers are invited to dine "Chuck Wagon Style" in a quaint Western atmosphere. Enjoy your favorite cocktails in the unique Gaslight Bar or the Longbranch Saloon where top names in the entertainment world will entertain you. The policy of giving the people what they want in quality... price... and service... has made the Midway Chuck Wagon the outstanding eating and entertainment attraction of the West.
